docs.abstract: Kyle Dolan opens our solving week.
docs.snippet: Kyle Dolan opens our solving week.
docs.lead_paragraph: MONDAY PUZZLE — Please help me welcome back the constructor Kyle Dolan, and congratulations to him for hitting for the cycle, which means that he now has a puzzle published in The New York Times for each day of the week.

docs.abstract: The former Atlanta officer, Garrett Rolfe, faces 11 charges, including murder and aggravated assault with a deadly weapon. He was fired on Saturday less than 24 hours after the fatal shooting.
docs.snippet: The former Atlanta officer, Garrett Rolfe, faces 11 charges, including murder and aggravated assault with a deadly weapon. He was fired on Saturday less than 24 hours after the fatal shooting.
docs.lead_paragraph: [Here’s what you need to know about the death of Rayshard Brooks.]

headline.main: Officer Charged With Murder in Rayshard Brooks Killing

docs.abstract: On Juneteenth, a holiday that honors the end of slavery in America, the vice president said that “all lives matter’’ but twice declined to say that black lives matter.
docs.snippet: On Juneteenth, a holiday that honors the end of slavery in America, the vice president said that “all lives matter’’ but twice declined to say that black lives matter.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Vice President Mike Pence twice refused to say that “black lives matter” during an interview on a Philadelphia television station on Friday, insisting instead that “all lives matter in a very real sense.”

headline.main: Pence Won’t Say the Words ‘Black Lives Matter’ in an Interview
headline.print_headline: Pence Won’t Say ‘Black Lives Matter’ in a Juneteenth Interview

docs.abstract: It increasingly resembles a Washington version of the Green Zone that sheltered American and Iraqi officials in Baghdad.
docs.snippet: It increasingly resembles a Washington version of the Green Zone that sheltered American and Iraqi officials in Baghdad.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump was furious when news got out last weekend that as protesters gathered outside the White House he had been rushed to an underground bunker. But now, as crowds keep coming back to demonstrate, the entire White House seems to be turning into one.

headline.main: Security Concerns Give the White House a Fortified New Look
headline.print_headline: The People’s House Is Now an Embattled President’s Fortress

docs.abstract: The social network said it was designating the antigovernment movement as a dangerous organization.
docs.snippet: The social network said it was designating the antigovernment movement as a dangerous organization.
docs.lead_paragraph: Facebook said on Tuesday that it took down a network of accounts, groups and pages connected to an antigovernment movement in the United States that encourages violence.

docs.abstract: The president issued a thinly veiled threat to anyone planning to demonstrate at his campaign rally on Saturday, but drew no distinction between peaceful protesters and “looters or lowlifes.”
docs.snippet: The president issued a thinly veiled threat to anyone planning to demonstrate at his campaign rally on Saturday, but drew no distinction between peaceful protesters and “looters or lowlifes.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump struck a combative stance on Friday for the holiday dedicated to the end of slavery, issuing a thinly veiled threat against protesters who have been marching against systemic racism and may show up at his campaign rally on Saturday in Tulsa, Okla., and warning that disruptions would not be tolerated.

headline.main: Trump’s Juneteenth Tweet: A Warning to Protesters at His Tulsa Rally
headline.print_headline: Trump Lumps Peaceful Protesters In With ‘Looters’ in Twitter Threat

byline.original: By Annie Karni and Michael D. Shear

docs.abstract: Samira Nasr, a former Vanity Fair fashion director, is leaving Condé Nast to take a key job at Hearst Magazines.
docs.snippet: Samira Nasr, a former Vanity Fair fashion director, is leaving Condé Nast to take a key job at Hearst Magazines.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hearst Magazines named Samira Nasr as the next editor of the U.S. edition of Harper’s Bazaar on Tuesday, the first time that a woman of color will hold the top job at the 153-year-old fashion publication.

headline.main: Harper’s Bazaar Appoints First Woman of Color as Top Editor
headline.print_headline: Harper’s Bazaar Picks First Woman of Color as Top Editor

docs.abstract: In addition to declaring solidarity, the fast-food industry could make changes to protect the health and safety of black employees.
docs.snippet: In addition to declaring solidarity, the fast-food industry could make changes to protect the health and safety of black employees.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week, Gushers and Fruit by the Foot, two fruit candies from the 1990s, now manufactured by General Mills, joined forces on Twitter to announce a deep commitment to … something.

headline.main: Food Brands Tweet #BlackLivesMatter, but What’s Behind the Words?
headline.print_headline: Food Brands Post Tweets, But What Do They Mean?

docs.abstract: The competition’s organizers were told that players in England wanted to demonstrate their backing for the anti-racism movement when games resume next week.
docs.snippet: The competition’s organizers were told that players in England wanted to demonstrate their backing for the anti-racism movement when games resume next week.
docs.lead_paragraph: LEEDS, England — The captains of England’s leading soccer clubs have informed the Premier League that players intend to demonstrate their support for the Black Lives Matter movement when the competition resumes play next week.

headline.main: Premier League Captains Plan Show of Support for Black Lives Matter
headline.print_headline: Top Players  In England  Plan Tribute  To Protests

docs.abstract: The mayor and City Council pared $1 billion in funding for the Police Department, but nearly half of that would come from budgetary sleight of hand.
docs.snippet: The mayor and City Council pared $1 billion in funding for the Police Department, but nearly half of that would come from budgetary sleight of hand.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bowing to political pressure and a bleak fiscal reality that evoked municipal crises of decades past, New York City officials on Monday agreed to an austerity budget that includes drastic cuts to city services and a $1 billion shift of resources out of the New York Police Department.

headline.main: De Blasio and Council, Facing Fiscal Crisis Over Virus, Agree on Budget With Big Cuts

byline.original: By Dana Rubinstein and Jeffery C. Mays
